"review_level": "None",
"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:5.18.1.2.1\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">5.18.1.2.1</span> Lid, cover</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Reference:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">צָמִיד</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(tsamid)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num19:15\">NUM 19:15</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0492_storiage_jar.jpg\" alt=\"Storage jar with lid\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Storage jar with lid (Metropolitan Museum of Art, CC0, MMA)</figcaption></figure>The lid was a cover made to fit tightly over the opening of a pot or jar. In some cases the lid was secured by tying it to the container.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The Hebrew word <em>tsamid</em> normally means a kind of bracelet worn as jewelry (see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">10.5.2 Bracelet, armlet, anklet&lt;REALIA:10.5.2&gt;</a>). In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num19:15\">NUM 19:15</a>, however, it indicates the way a jar was covered. The translation of this verse should convey the idea that the vessel is not closed or covered and so foreign objects might fall into it. Possible models are <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> “Every jar and pot in the tent that has no lid on it also becomes unclean” and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Century Version\">NCV</abbr> “And every open jar or pot without a cover becomes unclean.” In this verse the Hebrew word <em>pathil</em>, which describes the situation of the lid relative to the vessel, is expressed by some translations as “tied” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New American Standard Bible\">NASB</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised English Bible (1989)\">REB</abbr>, Luther, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Italian Common Language Version\">ITCL</abbr>). Others choose a more general term, such as “fastened” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Revised Standard Version (1989)\">NRSV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr>). Another model for the whole verse is “Any jar or pot that is not closed tightly becomes unclean.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
